   Nalini, M. and Subramanian, Siva R.},
Book-Group-Author = {IEEE},
Title = {Enhancing Healthcare Data Security in the Cloud: Integrating ML-Based
   Intrusion Detection Systems},
Booktitle = {2024 2ND WORLD CONFERENCE ON COMMUNICATION \& COMPUTING, WCONF 2024},
Year = {2024},
Abstract = {Technology integration, but particularly the merging of health care data
   systems (HCDS) with Cloud Computing, becomes crucial for the proper data
   management in developing healthcare system. The integration yields
   notable benefits including improved patient care, simplified
   administrative procedures and informed decision-making within healthcare
   organizations. Cloud computing also has scalability, flexibility and
   cost-effectiveness, so it becomes the best alternative for keeping and
   analyzing the big amounts of healthcare data. Nevertheless, the shift in
   paradigm leads to data security and privacy issues, which require strong
   security controls for sensitive health data. This research paper
   concerns optimizing HCDS using Cloud Computing to provide data
   management, accessibility, and scalability in the Healthcare industry.
   It studies the utilization of Technology, specifically Cloud Computing,
   in improving Health Care administration systems, reducing paperwork, and
   creating a centralized platform for efficient health care organization
   administration. The focus area is concerned with the security issues
   raised by keeping healthcare data on the cloud, which covers the
   creation and implementation of such as encryption, access controls and
   intrusion detection. The research utilizes the latest technologies such
   as AI and ML to enhance healthcare data on the cloud security. The
   NSL-KDD benchmark dataset is used to maturely apply and analyse ML
   models such as RF, SVM, and LR. The results show the models' capacity to
   distinguish Denial of Service, Probe, Remote and Local, and User to Root
   attacks. Compared to other ML models, in particular Random Forest is a
   leading one in performance in all attack types.},
